<article>
    <h1>Green Lip Mus&#xAD;sels Bag with Sig&#xAD;na&#xAD;ture Chilli Pomelo Sauce ($28 for 700g)</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20200920/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-09-20"><time>2020-09-20</time></a>
        - <span>LIFE | FOOD &amp; DRINK</span>
        - <span role="byline"></span>
    </section>

    <p>The sauce is the high­light. It was cre­ated for Blue Lo­tus Chi­nese Eat­ing House’s chilli crab when that restau­rant opened seven years ago and is an ap­petis­ing blend of sour, sweet and spicy, with a good dose of aro­mat­ics, to tan­ta­lise the palate.</p>
    <p>A top­ping of fresh pomelo sacs is the fin­ish­ing touch, adding sub­tle notes of sweet­ness and acid­ity.</p>
    <p>The sauce is so pop­u­lar that it has been used in var­i­ous other dishes in the group’s out­lets, in­clud­ing in the seafood boils here.</p>
    <p>It would have worked with any seafood and I chose mus­sels be­cause they are my favourite and, un­like crab or prawns, did not need peel­ing.</p>
    <p>At the bot­tom, un­der­neath the seafood and covered by the sauce, were pieces of corn and new pota­toes, which made the dish pretty sub­stan­tial.</p>
    <p>It’s a good idea to get a plate of Fried Man­tou ($6 for six) to soak up any re­main­ing gravy be­cause, trust me, you do not want to let it go to waste.</p>

